  <section class="block reveal" id="edges">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="sec-num">05</span><h2 class="sec-title">Every edge &amp; loophole</h2></div>
    <p class="lede">The small, legal advantages most athletes leave on the table. Use all of them.</p>
    <div class="loot">
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Farm the uncapped trio</h4><p>Pan Am President's Cup (G3, own continent) and the odd-year GP Challenge (G2) sit outside the 40-point cap. So does the Continental Junior Championship. Win these for points that "don't count against" the open limit.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Three divisions feed −68</h4><p>−63, −68 and −74 World results all cumulate into the −68 Olympic ranking. He can hunt points wherever the field is softest among them — most practically −63 (see §10). Lock −68 as his Olympic category so they land correctly.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Junior-medal carryover</h4><p>Youth Olympic / Junior Worlds / Continental Junior <em>medals</em> carry into the senior Olympic ranking the year he turns 17 (2027): YOG gold 60, Junior Worlds gold 40, Continental Junior gold 20. Possibly free banked points — verify his medals fall in the valid window.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Dakar 2026 YOG is a double-dip</h4><p>Making the 2026 Youth Olympic team is both a route into the 2027 Senior Team Trials <em>and</em> a carryover-points event (YOG gold = 60). Two birds.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>The reallocation backdoor catches unused continental seats</h4><p>He can't <em>enter</em> the Pan Am qualifier — but if continental seats go unfilled, they reallocate to the next-highest-ranked eligible athlete "from any continent" on the Jan 2028 ranking. A high USA ranking can scoop one. Ranking high pays off even on the closed pathway.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Host 4-seed at the Games</h4><p>Qualify through the host quota and he's seeded 4th in the LA bracket — a softer Olympic draw on top of the seat itself.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Steer the host-division choice</h4><p>USATKD tends to "spend" host seats on divisions they <em>won't</em> fill by ranking. If the USA's other men look likely to rank-qualify, −68 becomes the natural host pick — so being the clear −68 #1 with podium proof positions him perfectly.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>Beating names after the reset counts double</h4><p>USATKD explicitly credits wins over ranked athletes — and specifically beating established names <em>after the ranking reset</em>. A newcomer's upset wins are exactly what the rubric rewards.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>The Team Trials second chance</h4><p>At U.S. Team Trials, a Day-1 semifinalist who doesn't win can contest one division up or down on Day 2 — a second bite at a national team berth (−63 or −74 from −68).</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><div><h4>GP host invite</h4><p>If the USA hosts a Grand Prix Series or Challenge (e.g., Charlotte), the host country gets an extra invite — a possible side door into a G6 he isn't yet ranked for.</p></div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

